WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:12.300
Domino's Starter Level, a pretty face by John

00:12.300 --> 00:15.920
S. Scott, read by Jennifer J. Myers.

00:18.990 --> 00:23.320
Copyright Oxford University Press 2003

00:25.040 --> 00:32.760
Chapter 1 Zoe is angry Zoe is 17

00:32.760 --> 00:39.200
years old. She works in a bookstore in the little town
  
00:39.200 --> 00:45.600
of Newport. Zoe likes books, and she likes

00:45.600 --> 00:50.860
her work, but after work she likes to act
 
00:50.860 --> 00:57.140
in plays with the Newport players. The Newport

00:57.140 --> 01:03.460
players do six plays every year, and Zoe is
  
01:03.460 --> 01:07.820
in most of them. Some plays are exciting,

01:08.580 --> 01:16.480
and some plays are famous. This week the play is Romeo
  
01:16.480 --> 01:24.000
and Juliet by William Shakespeare. A lot of

01:24.000 --> 01:27.840
people are coming to see it, Zoe thinks.

01:28.860 --> 01:30.000
I must act

01:30.000 --> 01:38.380
well. Mike is 18 years old. He is

01:38.380 --> 01:43.100
a student at Newport College, and he likes

01:43.100 --> 01:47.100
writing. One day he

01:47.100 --> 01:51.160
wants to write plays for the theatre and

01:51.160 --> 01:59.500
for television. One day I want to be famous, he thinks.
  
02:01.560 --> 02:07.620
Newport has a newspaper. The Newport Weekly News

02:07.620 --> 02:13.680
is its name, and Mike's Aunt Peggy is the editor.
 
02:14.800 --> 02:22.160
One morning she phones Mike. Do you want

02:22.160 --> 02:26.560
to write a review of Romeo and Juliet

02:26.560 --> 02:29.100
for the newspaper Mike?

02:30.400 --> 02:36.040
She asks him. The Newport players are doing

02:36.040 --> 02:39.340
the play tonight at the little theatre.

02:41.280 --> 02:47.820
Yes, please Aunt Peggy. Mike says, thanks for

02:47.820 --> 02:54.540
asking me. That evening he goes to Newport's

02:54.540 --> 02:57.140
little theatre to see the play.

02:59.160 --> 03:03.500
Mike goes into the theatre and sits at

03:03.500 --> 03:08.280
the front. He gets out his notebook and

03:08.280 --> 03:13.040
pen, ready to write notes for his review.

03:14.320 --> 03:17.780
There are a lot of people in the

03:17.780 --> 03:27.200
audience. Five minutes later the play begins. Zoe

03:27.200 --> 03:30.860
acts the part of Juliet's mother.

03:31.860 --> 03:36.380
She knows all her words and speaks them

03:36.380 --> 03:44.500
well. Mike is watching her. She's very pretty

03:44.500 --> 03:48.960
and she's doing her best, he thinks.

03:49.960 --> 03:53.720
But it's not easy to act the part

03:53.720 --> 03:58.700
of an older woman. She's only 16 or

03:58.700 --> 04:03.200
17 years old and we all know it.

04:04.880 --> 04:10.500
He begins to write in his notebook. Two

04:10.500 --> 04:15.000
hours later the play ends and the audience

04:15.000 --> 04:16.320
leaves the theatre.

04:17.740 --> 04:22.200
Mike goes home and writes his review for

04:22.200 --> 04:26.920
the newspaper. He doesn't feel very happy.

04:28.760 --> 04:33.400
It was a good play, but what can

04:33.400 --> 04:36.580
I say about the girl acting the part

04:36.580 --> 04:39.880
of Juliet's mother, he thinks.

04:40.880 --> 04:45.080
I want to be kind, but I must

04:45.080 --> 04:46.920
be honest too.

04:49.560 --> 04:53.980
At the bookstore on Friday, Zoe reads Mike's

04:53.980 --> 04:58.100
review of the play in the Newport Weekly News.
 
04:59.340 --> 05:03.820
And Zoe Baker acts the part of Juliet's

05:03.820 --> 05:08.640
mother. She has a pretty face and she

05:08.640 --> 05:10.340
speaks her words well.

05:11.160 --> 05:14.260
But she is a young girl in an

05:14.260 --> 05:19.020
older woman's costume and we all know it.

05:20.100 --> 05:23.320
She can never make me believe differently.

05:24.680 --> 05:30.300
Zoe is angry. She looks at the name

05:30.300 --> 05:34.380
under the review. Mike Morrison.

05:36.040 --> 05:43.140
Who is this Mike Morrison? She thinks. What

05:43.140 --> 05:45.940
does he know about acting?

05:54.060 --> 05:59.320
Chapter Two. Zoe has an idea.

06:04.820 --> 06:10.180
On Tuesday evening, the next week, Zoe and

06:10.180 --> 06:14.260
her friend Annie are drinking coffee in the

06:14.260 --> 06:15.580
Newport Cafe.

06:16.900 --> 06:22.420
Annie is a student at Newport College and

06:22.420 --> 06:27.880
sometimes in the evenings she and Zoe meet at the cafe.
 
06:30.220 --> 06:34.700
Suddenly, Zoe sees a boy sitting at a

06:34.700 --> 06:36.580
table across the room.

06:38.260 --> 06:44.580
Who's that boy? She asks Annie. Annie laughs.

06:45.340 --> 06:48.540
Do you like him? He has a nice

06:48.540 --> 06:54.340
face, she says. His name's Mike. I often

06:54.340 --> 06:56.060
see him at the college.

06:57.060 --> 07:06.280
Mike, Zoe says. Mike who? Mike Morrison, Annie says.
  
07:07.600 --> 07:14.580
That's Mike Morrison, Zoe says. She is furious.

07:14.580 --> 07:19.540
Yes, why? Annie asks.

07:20.640 --> 07:25.520
He writes reviews for the Newport Weekly News.

07:26.660 --> 07:27.460
Zoe says.

07:28.200 --> 07:33.920
That's right. Annie says. His aunt is the

07:33.920 --> 07:36.780
editor. He... oh.

07:37.780 --> 07:42.980
She stops suddenly and looks at Zoe. The

07:42.980 --> 07:45.360
review of Romeo and Juliet.

07:46.420 --> 07:52.460
Right, Zoe says. Do you remember it? Zoe

07:52.460 --> 07:56.240
Baker acts the part of Juliet's mother.

07:56.860 --> 08:00.620
She has a pretty face and she speaks

08:00.620 --> 08:04.960
her words well. But she is a young

08:04.960 --> 08:11.840
girl in an older woman's costume and we all know it.
 
08:13.040 --> 08:18.220
Nice face or no nice face. I hate

08:18.220 --> 08:21.300
him. Annie laughs.

08:22.040 --> 08:27.620
Okay, go and tell him, she says. Go

08:27.620 --> 08:31.200
and say, I hate you, Mike Morrison.

08:32.200 --> 08:37.860
You write stupid reviews for the newspaper. Go on.
 
08:39.180 --> 08:42.040
But Zoe isn't laughing.

08:43.360 --> 08:49.400
Yes, all right. She says furiously and she

08:49.400 --> 08:51.760
begins to get up from her chair.

08:52.760 --> 08:55.940
Then she stops suddenly.

08:57.060 --> 09:01.860
What's wrong? Annie asks. Are you afraid?

09:02.920 --> 09:09.380
No, Zoe says. I have a better idea.

09:10.200 --> 09:14.100
Does he come into this cafe often?

09:16.160 --> 09:22.120
Every Tuesday and Thursday evening, I think. Annie says.
  
09:23.160 --> 09:26.220
He has a writing class at the college

09:26.220 --> 09:29.800
and he comes here after it finishes.

09:32.200 --> 09:34.940
Zoe thinks for a minute or two.

09:36.680 --> 09:43.260
That's very interesting, she says at last. Is

09:43.260 --> 09:45.080
it? Annie says.

09:46.480 --> 09:51.120
She looks across at Mike Morrison, then at Zoe.
 
09:52.680 --> 09:57.200
Why is it interesting? What are you thinking

09:57.200 --> 09:57.960
of doing?

09:59.540 --> 10:04.800
Tell me, am I a good actress? Zoe

10:04.800 --> 10:09.100
asks. Yes, you are, Annie says.

10:10.080 --> 10:16.320
But, okay, Zoe says. I'm a good actress

10:16.320 --> 10:19.780
and I want to prove it to Mr.

10:19.780 --> 10:22.520
Mike, nice face Morrison.

10:24.720 --> 10:28.620
How do you want to do that? Annie asks.
 
10:29.900 --> 10:35.900
Zoe smiles and begins to tell Annie about her idea.
 
10:44.100 --> 10:49.020
Chapter 3, A Difficult Interviews

10:54.440 --> 10:59.080
On Thursday, Mike comes to the Newport Cafe

10:59.080 --> 11:01.020
after his writing class.

11:01.980 --> 11:05.940
He asks for a cup of coffee, then

11:05.940 --> 11:08.500
starts to read one of his books.

11:10.140 --> 11:14.940
Some minutes later, a woman comes into the cafe.
 
11:16.340 --> 11:20.640
She is carrying a magazine under her arm.

11:21.860 --> 11:26.520
At first, Mike does not see the woman.

11:27.520 --> 11:31.360
Then, she comes across to his table.

11:33.200 --> 11:39.240
Hello, she says. Are you Mike Morrison?

11:41.240 --> 11:47.120
Mike is surprised. Yes, he says. That's me.

11:48.400 --> 11:53.820
The woman smiles. Can I sit at this

11:53.820 --> 11:56.140
table? She asks.

11:57.220 --> 12:00.720
Yes, of course, Mike says.

12:02.200 --> 12:07.500
My name is Kate Lawson, the woman says.

12:08.460 --> 12:13.820
I'm the editor of Yes magazine. Do you know it?
 
12:15.160 --> 12:19.340
She sits down and puts the magazine on

12:19.340 --> 12:21.280
the table in front of Mike.

12:22.160 --> 12:27.280
Yes, I know it, Mike says. It's a

12:27.280 --> 12:29.580
magazine about famous people.

12:31.340 --> 12:36.720
That's right, Kate says. Do you want to

12:36.720 --> 12:38.480
write something for it?

12:39.040 --> 12:42.380
Can you do an interview for me?

12:43.920 --> 12:47.780
An interview? Mike says, surprised.

12:49.060 --> 12:51.500
Why are you asking me?

12:53.000 --> 12:58.160
You sometimes write theater reviews for the Newport

12:58.160 --> 13:01.120
Weekly newspaper, she says.

13:01.960 --> 13:02.800
Is that right?

13:03.840 --> 13:07.240
Yes, I do, he says.

13:08.580 --> 13:11.900
I want to write plays one day and,

13:12.240 --> 13:18.020
well, do this interview for my magazine then, she says.
 
13:19.140 --> 13:32.780
It's with a famous playwright. He lives in Newport.
 
13:32.780 --> 13:37.320
He lives quietly and doesn't go out very often.
 
13:38.220 --> 13:41.720
And he's famous for not talking to reporters

13:41.720 --> 13:43.980
from gossip magazines.

13:45.220 --> 13:47.420
He throws them out of his house.

13:49.040 --> 13:50.040
Kate laughs.

13:51.140 --> 13:54.040
Are you afraid? She says.

13:55.020 --> 13:59.900
Good reporters aren't afraid to do difficult interviews.

13:59.900 --> 14:04.360
You want to write play, don't you?

14:05.220 --> 14:09.700
Well, perhaps he can tell you something about

14:09.700 --> 14:10.800
playwriting.

14:12.420 --> 14:16.240
Mike thinks she's right.

14:17.200 --> 14:21.040
Perhaps I can learn something from Todd Marin.

14:22.800 --> 14:25.140
Okay, he says.

14:26.040 --> 14:27.460
When can I do it?

14:28.660 --> 14:31.780
Tomorrow morning, Kate says.

14:32.720 --> 14:36.840
You must tell Marin this interview is for

14:36.840 --> 14:42.580
yes magazine, but tell him after you get into the house.
 
14:43.240 --> 14:47.240
Okay? Okay, Mike says.

14:48.720 --> 14:51.300
End of side one.

14:54.740 --> 14:56.000
Side two.

15:05.240 --> 15:08.300
Chapter four, Todd Marin's house.

15:14.200 --> 15:18.980
Later that evening, Zoe is speaking to Annie

15:18.980 --> 15:19.920
on the phone.

15:22.140 --> 15:26.920
So I say to him, I'm the editor

15:26.920 --> 15:28.760
of yes magazine.

15:29.880 --> 15:32.980
And can you interview Todd Marin?

15:32.980 --> 15:35.560
Zoe tells Annie.

15:36.800 --> 15:39.840
Todd Marin, Annie says.

15:40.740 --> 15:44.640
But he throws gossip magazine reporters out of

15:44.640 --> 15:45.300
his house.

15:46.040 --> 15:50.280
I know, Zoe says laughing.

15:51.140 --> 15:54.840
And I want to stand outside his house

15:54.840 --> 16:00.580
and watch Todd Marin throw Mike Morrison out.

16:02.800 --> 16:08.120
The next morning, Mike goes to Todd Marin's house.
  
16:09.320 --> 16:12.800
It is a big house, and there are

16:12.800 --> 16:17.100
lots of bushes and tall trees in front of it.
  
16:19.120 --> 16:24.480
I don't like yes magazine very much, but

16:24.480 --> 16:28.200
this is an important interview, Mike thinks.

16:29.000 --> 16:32.900
And perhaps I can talk to Todd Marin

16:32.900 --> 16:34.480
about my play.

16:35.880 --> 16:38.780
Mike is writing a play for television.

16:41.240 --> 16:44.040
He walks up to the front door of

16:44.040 --> 16:44.540
the house.

16:45.540 --> 16:49.320
He is carrying his notebook, and he has

16:49.320 --> 16:52.480
a list of questions to ask the playwright.

16:53.480 --> 16:56.320
But he is a little afraid of the

16:56.320 --> 16:57.280
famous man.

16:58.860 --> 17:03.220
Zoe follows Mike to Todd Marin's house.

17:04.180 --> 17:08.600
She is careful, and she follows Mike very

17:08.600 --> 17:09.460
quietly.

17:10.680 --> 17:15.440
Zoe is acting the part of Kate Lawson again.
 
17:16.440 --> 17:20.460
She has a black wig over her hair,

17:21.560 --> 17:23.620
and she is wearing glasses.

17:26.040 --> 17:30.400
She hides behind one of the bushes in

17:30.400 --> 17:35.460
front of Todd Marin's house and watches Mike

17:35.460 --> 17:37.740
go to the front door.

17:38.980 --> 17:42.980
It is a big, dark house.

17:45.520 --> 17:49.780
This is funny, she thinks, smiling.

17:52.380 --> 17:55.700
When Todd Marin opens the door of his

17:55.700 --> 17:59.680
house, Mike begins to talk quickly.

18:01.320 --> 18:03.620
Hello, Mr. Marin.

18:04.500 --> 18:08.380
He says, I'm Mike Morrison.

18:09.560 --> 18:14.200
I'm a student at Newport College, and I

18:14.200 --> 18:15.500
want to write plays.

18:17.220 --> 18:20.680
Do you, Todd Marin says.

18:21.680 --> 18:26.360
And I write reviews in the Newport Weekly

18:26.360 --> 18:29.040
News, Mike tells him.

18:30.560 --> 18:35.240
What do you want from me, Todd Marin asks?
 
18:36.420 --> 18:41.420
Can I ask you some questions, Mike says?

18:42.600 --> 18:45.140
Why, Marin asks?

18:46.140 --> 18:49.180
Is it for the Newport Weekly News?

18:51.260 --> 18:53.300
That's a difficult question.

18:54.580 --> 18:57.360
What do I do now, Mike thinks?

18:58.880 --> 19:02.880
Do I tell him a lie, or do

19:02.880 --> 19:04.320
I tell him the truth?

19:06.680 --> 19:10.660
Then, after a second or two, he says,

19:12.400 --> 19:15.660
it's, or yes, magazine.

19:16.840 --> 19:22.140
Listen, I know it's a stupid magazine, but

19:22.140 --> 19:27.400
come into the house, Todd Marin says suddenly.

19:37.040 --> 19:40.940
Chapter 5 Zoe waits.

19:46.220 --> 19:51.480
Zoe is watching Mike and Todd Marin from

19:51.480 --> 19:52.840
behind a bush.

19:54.180 --> 19:58.940
She can see them, but she cannot hear them speaking.
 
20:00.880 --> 20:06.560
She sees Todd Marin open the door, and

20:06.560 --> 20:10.300
she sees Mike follow him into the house.

20:11.780 --> 20:13.720
Zoe smiles.

20:14.800 --> 20:19.620
Right, he's in the house, she thinks.

20:20.620 --> 20:25.420
Now, let's wait for Todd Marin to throw

20:25.420 --> 20:26.460
him out.

20:29.260 --> 20:33.040
Todd Marin takes Mike to his study.

20:34.380 --> 20:37.480
There are hundreds of books in the room,

20:38.440 --> 20:40.040
and a big desk.

20:42.590 --> 20:45.900
Todd goes and sits behind the desk.

20:47.920 --> 20:50.780
Thank you for telling me the truth.

20:52.080 --> 20:57.180
He says to Mike, I can see you're

20:57.180 --> 20:58.820
an honest young man.

20:59.800 --> 21:04.560
You can ask your questions, but not for

21:04.560 --> 21:05.920
yes, magazine.

21:07.180 --> 21:08.360
You're right.

21:09.440 --> 21:11.560
It is a stupid magazine.

21:12.560 --> 21:15.300
I hate gossip magazines.

21:16.460 --> 21:19.100
Why do people write for them?

21:20.580 --> 21:24.420
Because they pay a lot of money, I

21:24.420 --> 21:26.440
believe, Mike says.

21:27.860 --> 21:29.220
Todd Marin laughs.

21:30.220 --> 21:34.320
Yes, you're right again, he says.

21:35.460 --> 21:38.300
But you can write about me for the

21:38.300 --> 21:39.940
Newport Weekly News.

21:40.860 --> 21:41.760
Is that okay?

21:43.160 --> 21:48.560
Yes, that's okay, Mike says, and he smiles

21:48.560 --> 21:50.240
at Todd Marin happily.

21:51.540 --> 21:55.380
I like to help young writers with ideas

21:55.380 --> 21:56.500
when I can.

21:57.340 --> 21:58.440
Todd says kindly.

21:59.500 --> 22:00.260
Sit down.

22:01.460 --> 22:06.240
Mike sits down, puts his notebook on Todd's

22:06.240 --> 22:08.100
desk and opens it.

22:10.360 --> 22:13.720
I read your reviews in the newspaper sometimes,

22:14.600 --> 22:15.620
Todd says.

22:16.640 --> 22:18.100
They're very good.

22:19.700 --> 22:24.840
Well, I think they're okay, Mike says.

22:25.710 --> 22:27.940
But I want to write for the theater

22:27.940 --> 22:30.640
or TV and for movies.

22:31.520 --> 22:33.400
I'm writing a play now.

22:34.880 --> 22:36.000
Are you?

22:36.540 --> 22:39.200
Tell me about it, Todd said.

22:40.340 --> 22:41.480
Can I?

22:42.700 --> 22:47.580
Mike asks, well, it's about a boy and

22:47.580 --> 22:48.020
a girl.

22:48.980 --> 22:50.940
A boy and a girl?

22:51.800 --> 22:52.760
That's right.

22:55.000 --> 22:55.900
They...

22:55.900 --> 22:59.120
Todd Marin sits back in his chair to

22:59.120 --> 23:02.980
listen, and Mike tells him the plot of

23:02.980 --> 23:03.500
his play.

23:04.860 --> 23:10.200
Mike is very nervous, but Todd Marin does

23:10.200 --> 23:11.120
not speak.

23:12.520 --> 23:16.200
He smiles at Mike, and he listens to

23:16.200 --> 23:18.060
him very carefully.

23:20.040 --> 23:23.480
When at last, Mike stops speaking.

23:24.440 --> 23:27.080
Todd says, thank you.

23:27.800 --> 23:29.500
That's very interesting.

23:30.840 --> 23:34.820
It's a good story, and it's funny, too.

23:36.520 --> 23:39.200
But there are one or two things you

23:39.200 --> 23:41.240
can do to make it better.

23:42.120 --> 23:45.060
To begin with,

23:46.060 --> 23:49.560
Zoe stays behind the bush and waits.

23:50.800 --> 23:54.080
An hour goes by and nothing happens.

23:55.220 --> 23:57.180
She is getting impatient.

23:58.760 --> 24:03.280
What are they doing in there, she thinks?

24:04.480 --> 24:09.760
Todd Marin never gives interviews to gossip magazines.

24:10.760 --> 24:13.600
So what are they talking about?

24:15.880 --> 24:21.380
She remembers Mike Morrison's review of Romeo and

24:21.380 --> 24:23.260
Juliet in the newspaper.

24:24.580 --> 24:28.140
She remembers his words about her acting,

24:28.860 --> 24:32.680
and she wants to see his face when

24:32.680 --> 24:36.140
Todd Marin throws him out of the house.

24:37.760 --> 24:40.480
How long must I wait?

24:41.260 --> 24:46.140
She thinks impatiently.

24:52.460 --> 24:54.160
Chapter 6

24:55.060 --> 24:56.200
Telling the Truth

25:02.940 --> 25:05.380
After an hour and a half,

25:05.980 --> 25:10.680
Mike Morrison leaves Todd Marin's study and comes

25:10.680 --> 25:11.840
out of the house.

25:13.900 --> 25:18.380
He and the playwright are smiling, and Mike

25:18.380 --> 25:20.500
is saying, thank you.

25:21.560 --> 25:24.840
They talk for two or three minutes,

25:25.640 --> 25:28.880
and Zoe watches them from behind the bush.

25:29.740 --> 25:31.680
She is amazed.

25:33.360 --> 25:36.740
What's happening, she thinks?

25:37.500 --> 25:40.000
Why are they so friendly?

25:42.400 --> 25:46.260
After a minute or two more, they shake

25:46.260 --> 25:46.840
hands.

25:47.840 --> 25:52.280
Then Todd Marin goes back into the house,

25:53.160 --> 25:55.620
and Mike Morrison walks away.

25:57.520 --> 26:01.820
Mike sees Kate Lawson waiting for him.

26:02.800 --> 26:04.840
Oh, hello?

26:05.960 --> 26:07.000
He says nervously.

26:08.520 --> 26:11.480
He is surprised to see her so soon.

26:12.480 --> 26:15.020
Are you waiting for me?

26:16.220 --> 26:20.140
Yes, she says impatiently.

26:21.100 --> 26:23.540
I'm waiting for your interview.

26:25.370 --> 26:30.080
Look, I can't lie to you, he replies.

26:31.500 --> 26:34.620
There's no interview or yes magazine.

26:35.680 --> 26:40.480
Mr. Marin always refuses to talk to reporters

26:40.480 --> 26:42.080
from gossip magazine.

26:43.860 --> 26:47.100
But what Kate begins?

26:48.560 --> 26:52.260
What can two people talk about for an

26:52.260 --> 26:53.240
hour and a half?

26:54.160 --> 26:55.360
Mike says laughing.

26:56.140 --> 27:01.460
About writing, about characters, and about plot.

27:02.960 --> 27:06.920
Nothing for yes magazine, I'm afraid.

27:08.060 --> 27:13.380
Oh, I have my list of questions and

27:13.380 --> 27:15.100
Mr. Marin's answers.

27:16.280 --> 27:20.100
But my interview is for the Newport Weekly

27:20.100 --> 27:20.480
News.

27:21.740 --> 27:25.480
And I know a lot more about writing

27:25.480 --> 27:26.620
plays now.

27:27.620 --> 27:30.440
He's very interested in my play.

27:32.020 --> 27:33.540
Your play?

27:34.640 --> 27:36.220
Kate says furiously.

27:37.460 --> 27:42.860
Yes, I'm writing a play for TV, Mike

27:42.860 --> 27:43.260
says.

27:44.460 --> 27:46.940
And Mr. Marin wants to read it.

27:47.720 --> 27:51.240
He can help me with the characters and

27:51.240 --> 27:51.660
the plot.

27:53.460 --> 27:57.300
Well, that's nice, she says.

27:58.260 --> 28:03.560
Say hello to Mike Morrison, the famous playwright.

28:04.380 --> 28:08.060
He writes stupid reviews for the Newport Weekly

28:08.060 --> 28:08.460
News,

28:09.220 --> 28:11.000
but his plays are okay.

28:12.520 --> 28:15.700
You're angry, Mike says.

28:16.460 --> 28:20.880
Listen, I'm sorry about the interview for yes.

28:22.600 --> 28:23.580
Kate laughs.

28:24.320 --> 28:28.180
No, it's okay, she says.

28:29.220 --> 28:30.700
I'm not angry.

28:32.560 --> 28:36.860
And then she does something very strange.

28:37.680 --> 28:40.820
She takes off her hair.

28:42.060 --> 28:46.980
She's wearing a wig, Mike thinks, amazed.

28:48.320 --> 28:52.840
Next, she takes off her glasses and she

28:52.840 --> 28:54.160
smiles at Mike.

28:55.480 --> 28:57.960
And now he knows her.

28:59.160 --> 29:01.440
He begins to laugh.

29:02.680 --> 29:06.320
You're not Kate Lawson, he says.

29:08.780 --> 29:11.880
That's right, Zoe says.

29:12.820 --> 29:16.520
I'm a 17-year-old girl in an

29:16.520 --> 29:18.480
older woman's costume.

29:19.360 --> 29:23.880
Mr. Mike Morrison, review writer for the Newport

29:23.880 --> 29:25.220
Weekly News.

29:28.280 --> 29:31.320
Mike's face is very red now.

29:32.140 --> 29:33.820
He feels embarrassed.

29:35.160 --> 29:36.940
What a trick.

29:38.180 --> 29:42.080
So there is no Kate Lawson editor of

29:42.080 --> 29:44.900
Yes magazine, he says.

29:45.600 --> 29:50.000
No, there isn't, Zoe says, laughing.

29:50.760 --> 29:52.920
What do you think now?

29:54.060 --> 29:55.940
Does this prove something?

29:57.000 --> 29:58.860
Am I a good actress?

29:58.860 --> 30:04.120
Yes, you are a good actress.

30:04.980 --> 30:07.120
Mike says, laughing with her.

30:08.100 --> 30:10.720
And I'm going to put that in the

30:10.720 --> 30:12.520
Newport Weekly News.

30:13.820 --> 30:15.000
Are you?

30:15.880 --> 30:18.060
Zoe says, yes.

30:18.980 --> 30:21.960
And thanks for making me go and see

30:21.960 --> 30:25.100
Todd Marin, Mike tells her.

30:25.760 --> 30:28.300
He doesn't feel embarrassed anymore.

30:30.000 --> 30:32.980
Now I can get help with my play,

30:33.720 --> 30:34.300
he says.

30:35.180 --> 30:38.620
Come on, let's get a cup of coffee

30:38.620 --> 30:40.880
and I'm paying.

30:42.080 --> 30:48.040
Well, I can't refuse a free coffee, Zoe

30:48.040 --> 30:50.400
says, and she laughs.

30:52.500 --> 30:54.940
End of side two.

